  "prompt": "Can a country run without president?",
  "response": "Yes, a country can run without a president, depending on its governmental structure. There are various forms of governance that do not include a presidential position. For example:\n\n1. **Parliamentary Systems:** In parliamentary democracies, the head of government is often a prime minister, and there may not be a president at all, or a president may serve a largely ceremonial role.\n\n2. **Monarchies:** Some countries are constitutional monarchies where a king or queen serves as the head of state, while the government is run by a prime minister or a parliamentary system.\n\n3. **Collective Leadership:** Some nations may operate under a collective leadership model, such as a council or committee that governs without a single presidential figure.\n\n4. **Transitional Governments:** In times of political upheaval or transition, a country may temporarily function without a clear presidential leadership.\n\nIn these cases, governance relies on other political structures and institutions, which can take on the functions typically associated with a president.",
